specimen.notes: alternatively basking and patrolling the back border of the lot; Today Derek and I stood in the front yard and caught several Vanessa cardui as they flew by.  They have been extremely numerous for the past few warm days, and during the heat of the day they fly to the northwest very fast.  As the afternoon wanes, they begin to defend patches of sunlit pines along the back boundary of the lots on Nelson Way.  It is possible that both V. cardui and V. annabella (and even V. virginiensis) are exhibiting the same behaviors, but I only know that I caught one or two V. cardui.

specimen.notes: lying dead on the trail, already being swarmed by ants.  Took a photo to record data: Could also be Euphydryas chalcedon.  Saw 6-8 of those, all resting on the dry grass heads along the uphill (west-facing) side of the trail.  Also saw several Ringlets, an Orange-tip, and a Pale Swallowtail.  One checkerspot was dead and crushed on the trail, looking as if it had not finished drying its wings.  All the checkerspots were torpid, either with the coolness of late afternoon, or perhaps due to just emerging today.  Have photos of several.
